[4] Cholera - Uganda (refugee camps)
Date: Tue, 9 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200411090608.html>

Cholera Hits More IDPs
----------------------
The cholera epidemic that started from Pabbo IDP [internally displaced
person] camp has spread to Amuru camp, also in Kilak county, with 2 cases
reported. The Pabbo sub-county LC3 chief, Christopher Ojera, on Sun, 7 Nov
2004, said that a 66-year-old died of cholera in Zone C, bringing the death
toll to 3, since the outbreak in Oct 2004.
Ojera said 2 women from Pabbo camp spread the disease to Amuru camp. He
said the task force had put Amuru camp on a cholera alert. They advised
camp residents to maintain hygiene to control the epidemic.
He said there were 123 registered cases of cholera in Pabbo camp and the
situation might worsen.
[Byline: Chris Ochowun]
******
[5] Cholera - Uganda
Date: Fri, 4 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: AllAfrica.com and New Vision (Kampala) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200411040513.html>

Cholera Overwhelms Kilembe Hospital
-----------------------------------
Kilembe Hospital in Kasese district does not have enough personnel to
handle both routine work and cholera, which hit the district on Sat, 30 Oct
2004.
The medical superintendent, Dr. Julius Bamwine, on Mon, 1 Nov 2004 said the
number of cholera patients had increased from 26 on Sun, 31 Nov 2004, to
35, with 1 death reported.
"All cases are from Nyakasanga parish of Kasese town council," he said.
Nyakasanga is the most populated area of Kasese town.
The patients were being treated under a tent, which could not accommodate
all the patients. Some of the patients were lying outside the tent but
within the quarantine area.
[Byline: John Nzinjah]
******
[6] Cholera, Gastroenteritis - Philippines
Date: Sat, 6 Nov 2004
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Manila Times [edited]
<http://www.manilatimes.net/national/2004/nov/06/yehey/prov/20041106pro1.html>

Outbreak of gastroenteritis in Pangasinan is longest in memory
--------------------------------------------------------------
The outbreak of acute gastroenteritis in Pangasinan from May to Oct 2004
was the longest outbreak in recent memory, according to Health Secretary
Manuel Dayrit. Dayrit said an epidemic normally emerges in a certain area
but dies down after 1 or 2 weeks but the outbreak of acute gastroenteritis
in Pangasinan lasted for around 5 months.
Records of the Center for Health Development of the Department of Health
based at the Dagupan City Astrodome showed that there were 8819 acute
gastroenteritis cases that were recorded from 28 May to 22 Oct 2004, of
which 464 were confirmed to be cholera cases.
There were 55 persons who died, the biggest number was registered in
Bolinao at 12; followed by San Carlos City, 9; Malasiqui, 8; Mangaldan, 5;
Alaminos and Bugallon, 4 each; Basista and Mangatarem, 3 each; Bayambang,
2; and 1 each from Dagupan City, Santa Barbara, Aguilar, Balungao and Umingan.
He said the epidemic that happened in Tondo, Manila, occurred in October
and November 2004 only, which was put under control through the
chlorination of water that was distributed to the neighborhood. But the one
that occurred in Pangasinan, according to Dayrit, lasted for 5 months and
emerged as the longest outbreak in the country since the cholera outbreak
in 1948.
There were also cholera cases that were recorded in La Union and a few in
Ilocos Sur, but these were not as widespread as the cholera cases that were
noted in Pangasinan. Eduardo Janairo, the health department's regional
director, said the outbreak of acute gastroenteritis in Pangasinan started
in Malasiqui town when some 300 people were brought at one time to the
Pangasinan Provincial Hospital in San Carlos City.
Noting that this was quite unusual, Janairo sent Dr. Revelyn Cayabyab, a
regional epidemiologist, to Pangasinan to trace where the disease came from
and found that the _Vibrio cholerae_ bacterium may have been spawned by
intake of contaminated water drawn from wells near septic tanks. Janairo
said the epidemic has not stopped yet to date, but it merely took a
downtrend; it is sure to resurge in the next rainy season.
